+++ ESP8266 ESP-12E NodeMCU notes

+ Version I'm using:
++ ESP8266 ESP-12E NodeMCU Lua V3 CH340G WIFI Lua Wireless Development Board Module.
++ Bought from eBay
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NodeMCU

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+++ ESP8266 ESP-12E NodeMCU pins

Label   Pin:GPIO
D0      16          Tested with button to turn LED on or off.
D1      05
D2      04
D3      00
D4(TX)  02          Built in, on board LED
3V      3v output   Infrared receive: power
G       Ground      Infrared receive: ground
D5      14
D6      12          Out to a resister, to an LED, to ground.
D7(RX)  13          Infrared receive: input (Didn't work on D8 which is TX)
D8(TX)  15
RX      03
TX      01
G       Ground      To breadboard ground (-).
3V      3v output   To breadboard power (+).
------------------
Label   Pin:GPIO
S3      10
S2      09

GPIO (GP: General Purpose, IO: Input/Output)

Tested: button input using D0-D02

Tested keypad:
byte rowPins[ROWS] = { 5, 4,  0};    // D1 D2     D3
byte colPins[COLS] = {14, 3,  9};    // D5 D9(RX) S2
S2 did not work with the keypad because It echos column 1,4,7 values.
D8(TX) did not work with the keypad because It echos column 1,4,9 values.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+++ Infrared reader for ESP8266 NodeMCU

https://www.instructables.com/id/Universal-Remote-Using-ESP8266Wifi-Controlled/

+ Select "Include Library" from there select "Manage libraries"
++ Search for "IRremoteESP8266" and install it. I installed version 2.6.3.

------------------------
// Infrared settings

#include <IRremoteESP8266.h>
#include <IRrecv.h>
#include <IRutils.h>

int IR_PIN = 13;          // Pin D7
IRrecv irrecv(IR_PIN);
decode_results results;
------------------------
void setup() {
  ...
  irrecv.enableIRIn();
}
void loop() {
  ...
  if (irrecv.decode(&results)) {
    serialPrintUint64(results.value, 16);
    irrecv.resume();
  }
}
------------------------

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+++ To develop and test

+ Start the webserver which is used for the NodeMCU to make an HTTP request.
$ node webserver

+ Start the Arduino IDE.
+ Open program: HttpGetSync.ino.
+ Enter the WiFI password. Note, after updates, before uploading the repository, remove the password.

+ Plug the NodeMCU into the computer's USB device. For my USB device, I click the USB On button.
+ Open the serial monitor from the IDE: Tools/Serial Monitor.

+ Watch the monitor. Example:
+ Connecting to the WiFi network: BATCAVE
......................
++ WiFi connected on IP address: 192.168.1.79
...

